      "author_association": "MEMBER",
      "body": "`getentropy()` was chosen deliberately over `arc4random()` when this was introduced, see  https://github.com/bitcoin-core/secp256k1/pull/748#discussion_r603295709 for the discussion.\r\n\r\n> `getentropy()`, which is not intended to be used by user code. See OpenBSD's [man page](https://man.openbsd.org/getentropy.2):\r\n> \r\n> > [getentropy](https://man.openbsd.org/getentropy.2#getentropy~2)() is not intended for regular code; use the [arc4random(3)](https://man.openbsd.org/arc4random.3) family of functions instead.\r\n\r\nHm, I don't think \"regular code\" means \"user code\". This is a syscall after all, if it is not supposed to be called by user code who else should call it?\r\n \r\n> [getentropy](https://man.openbsd.org/getentropy.2#getentropy)() fills a buffer with high-quality entropy, which can be used as input for process-context pseudorandom generators like [arc4random(3)](https://man.openbsd.org/arc4random.3).\r\n\r\nTogether with the above quote, I read this as \"Use `getentropy()` for seeding PRGs because it's high-quality, but if you want PRG output, then use `arc4random()`. But this distinction is a bit arbitrary, to be honest. And it's wrong because it contradicts the implementation of `getentropy()`, which has [always used `arc4random()`](https://github.com/openbsd/src/commit/eacbc5b32cfe3ca4de47833fa1b4b0efc9b3080a). ",
